Excellent. This is exactly how production systems should be managed — control index size + control retention instead of letting disks explode.

You have a single Elasticsearch node, so we’ll design ILM optimized for that reality.

⸻

🎯 Goal

We will:
	•	Rollover index at 5GB OR 1 day
	•	Keep logs for 30 days
	•	Delete automatically after 30 days
	•	Use 0 replicas (single node)
	•	Avoid shard explosion

⸻

🏗 Architecture Model (Single Node Best Practice)
	•	1 primary shard
	•	0 replicas
	•	Hot phase only
	•	Delete phase after retention

No warm/cold nodes since you only have one server.

⸻

✅ STEP 1 — Create ILM Policy

Run in Kibana Dev Tools:

PUT _ilm/policy/filebeat_policy
{
  "policy": {
    "phases": {
      "hot": {
        "actions": {
          "rollover": {
            "max_size": "5gb",
            "max_age": "1d"
          }
        }
      },
      "delete": {
        "min_age": "30d",
        "actions": {
          "delete": {}
        }
      }
    }
  }
}

What this means:
	•	If index reaches 5GB → new index created
	•	If 1 day passes → new index created
	•	After 30 days → index deleted automatically

Clean. Predictable. Controlled.

⸻

✅ STEP 2 — Create Index Template

This connects ILM to new indices.

PUT _index_template/filebeat_template
{
  "index_patterns": ["filebeat-*"],
  "template": {
    "settings": {
      "number_of_shards": 1,
      "number_of_replicas": 0,
      "index.lifecycle.name": "filebeat_policy",
      "index.lifecycle.rollover_alias": "filebeat"
    }
  }
}


⸻

✅ STEP 3 — Create First Write Index (Bootstrap)

This is important. ILM rollover requires alias.

PUT filebeat-000001
{
  "aliases": {
    "filebeat": {
      "is_write_index": true
    }
  }
}

Now:
	•	Filebeat must write to alias: filebeat
	•	Elasticsearch manages real indices internally

⸻

✅ STEP 4 — Update Filebeat Output

In filebeat.yml:

output.elasticsearch:
  hosts: ["http://ELASTIC_SERVER_IP:9200"]
  username: "filebeat_user"
  password: "password"
  index: "filebeat"
setup.ilm.enabled: false

Important:
	•	We disable Filebeat ILM
	•	We use our custom ILM

Restart Filebeat on all servers:

systemctl restart filebeat


⸻

🔎 How To Monitor ILM

Check rollover status:

GET filebeat-*/_ilm/explain

Check policy:

GET _ilm/policy/filebeat_policy

Check current index sizes:

GET _cat/indices/filebeat-*?h=index,docs.count,store.size


⸻

📊 How To Decide Proper Size & Retention

Let’s calculate correctly.

If you ingest:
	•	10GB per day
	•	30 days retention
→ 300GB storage required

On single node:
	•	Always keep 30–40% disk free
	•	Never exceed 70% disk usage

If disk is 500GB:
	•	Safe usable = ~350GB

So 30d retention for 10GB/day = OK

If disk is 200GB:
	•	You must reduce retention to 14 days

⸻

⚡ Advanced Production Advice (Strong Opinion)

For single node:
	•	Keep rollover between 3GB–5GB
	•	Never exceed 1 primary shard per index
	•	Never use replicas
	•	Keep retention under disk safety threshold

Shards kill clusters faster than volume does.

⸻

🚨 Why This Will Also Help Your Filebeat Stopping Issue

When indices grow too large:
	•	Merges become heavy
	•	Write threadpool blocks
	•	Filebeat backpressure happens
	•	Beats look like “stopped”

ILM stabilizes ingestion performance.

